  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Localized Immediate Drought Response</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Irregular rains during the 2009 growing season resulted in a harvest amounting to less than a quarter of annual household food requirements. In the most vulnerable regions of the country, food stocks had run out by April 2010 and, already impoverished by the successive years of failed harvests, households began resorting to negative coping mechanisms. Mercy Corps is focusing on using local/regional resources in a year-long response to the crisis in two separate but crucial ways. First, food assistance procured in or near Niger is provided through distributions, avoiding the delays associated with US-sourced commodities. Second, the program strengthens local mechanisms for maintaining and releasing emergency resources, such as cereal banks and the Government of Niger&#x2019;s early warning and response system. Through the first objective, food distributions increase food availability; through the second, the program ensures that a more robust safety net remains in place.</narrative>
  </description>
